Joshua Schache (/ˈʃæki/ [/wiki/Help:IPA/English] SHAK-ee
[/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key];[1] born 21 August 1997) is an
Australian rules footballer [/wiki/Australian_rules_football] who formerly
played professionally for the Brisbane Lions [/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], the Western
Bulldogs [/wiki/Western_Bulldogs] and Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club]
in the Australian Football League [/wiki/Australian_Football_League] (AFL).


EARLY LIFE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]

Schache was born in Adelaide, South Australia [/wiki/Adelaide,_South_Australia]
to mother Rachel and father Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache].[2] He started
playing Auskick [/wiki/Auskick] when he was in grade five. He attended high
school at Assumption College Kilmore [/wiki/Assumption_College,_Kilmore] and
later Goulburn Valley Grammar School [/wiki/Goulburn_Valley_Grammar_School]. His
late father, Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache], also played with Brisbane in the
early 1990s.[3][4][5]

Josh spent his early youth as a ruckman/forward for the Seymour Lions, a club
based in the Seymour District Junior Football League. He played with the Murray
Bushrangers [/wiki/Murray_Bushrangers] in the TAC Cup [/wiki/TAC_Cup] until he
was selected to join the Brisbane Lions with the second pick in the 2015 AFL
draft [/wiki/2015_AFL_draft].[4]

Schache is left-footed, 199 centimetres (78 in) tall and weighs 96 kilograms
(212 lb).[6]

He won the Larke Medal [/wiki/Larke_Medal] for his performance in the NAB AFL
Under-18 Championships in 2015, where he also he kicked a record 24 goals.[6]


AFL CAREER

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=2]]

In the first two years of his career at the Brisbane Lions
[/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], Schache played 27 games and kicked 25 goals. During 2017
there was speculation that he would request a trade to a Victorian club, but at
the end of the season his manager shut down speculation, insisting that he would
not be requesting a trade. Despite this, Brisbane later announced they would be
exploring trade options for Schache in the forthcoming trade period. In the
final minutes of the trade period, Schache was traded to the Western Bulldogs
for pick 25 and 40 despite being contracted until 2019 at the Brisbane
Lions.[7]Schache overcame niggling injuries during the first half of 2018. After
strong performances in the VFL he was elevated to the senior side where he
finished the season with 17 goals in 13 games.[8]Schache had a breakout year in
2019, kicking 24 goals from 14 games, only being omitted from the side due to
concussion protocols. Schache played in the 2019 Elimination Final against club
rivals, Greater Western Sydney. After playing his career best year, Schache only
managed to play two senior games in 2020, kicking 2 goals.

After a one-off appearance earlier in 2021, he returned to the senior side in
the middle of the season, successfully moving to become a key defender.[9]
Schache managed to play every game for the rest of the year, as a defender too,
including the clubs impressive climb to the Grand Final. Schache was moved back
to the forward line for the 2021 finals [/wiki/2021_AFL_finals_series], kicking
4 goals and shutting down prominent key defenders such as Aliir Aliir
[/wiki/Aliir_Aliir] of Port Adelaide [/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club].[10] He
played in the Western Bulldogs' 2021 Grand Final [/wiki/2021_AFL_Grand_Final]
team.[11]

Following the 2022 AFL season [/wiki/2022_AFL_season], Schache was traded to
Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club] on the last day of the trade
period.[12] Schache managed only four games across two seasons for the Demons.
When Melbourne failed to make finals for the first time since 2020, Schache was
delisted at the conclusion of the 2024 AFL season [/wiki/2024_AFL_season].[13]

In 2025, Schache will play for the Doncaster East Football Club
[/wiki/Doncaster_East_Football_Club] in the Eastern Football Netball League
[/wiki/Eastern_Football_Netball_League] (EFNL).[14]

TOPICS IN THE NEWS

Azzi Fudd
[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e6/Azzi_Fudd_2025.jpg/120px-Azzi_Fudd_2025.jpg]/wiki/File:Azzi_Fudd_2025.jpg
Azzi Fudd
 * A nightclub roof collapse [/wiki/Jet_Set_nightclub_roof_collapse] in Santo
   Domingo [/wiki/Santo_Domingo], the Dominican Republic, kills more than 90
   people.
 * In basketball [/wiki/Basketball], the UConn Huskies
   [/wiki/UConn_Huskies_women%27s_basketball] win
   [/wiki/2025_NCAA_Division_I_women%27s_basketball_championship_game] the NCAA
   Division I women's championship
   [/wiki/2025_NCAA_Division_I_women%27s_basketball_tournament] (Most
   Outstanding Player
   [/wiki/NCAA_Division_I_basketball_tournament_Most_Outstanding_Player] Azzi
   Fudd [/wiki/Azzi_Fudd] pictured) and the Florida Gators
   [/wiki/Florida_Gators_men%27s_basketball] win
   [/wiki/2025_NCAA_Division_I_men%27s_basketball_championship_game] the men's
   championship [/wiki/2025_NCAA_Division_I_men%27s_basketball_tournament].
 * South Korea's Constitutional Court [/wiki/Constitutional_Court_of_Korea]
   removes [/wiki/Impeachment_of_Yoon_Suk_Yeol] Yoon Suk Yeol
   [/wiki/Yoon_Suk_Yeol] as the president of South Korea
   [/wiki/President_of_South_Korea], following his earlier declaration of
   martial law [/wiki/2024_South_Korean_martial_law_crisis].
 * US president Donald Trump [/wiki/Donald_Trump] announces trade tariffs
   [/wiki/Tariffs_in_the_second_Trump_administration] on most countries.

Ongoing:
 * Gaza war [/wiki/Gaza_war]
 * M23 campaign [/wiki/M23_campaign_(2022%E2%80%93present)]

April 9, 2025 (2025-04-09) (Wednesday)
 * edit
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Current_events/2025_April_9&action=edit&editintro=Portal:Current_events/Edit_instructions]
 * history
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Current_events/2025_April_9&action=history]
 * watch
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Current_events/2025_April_9&action=watch]

Business and economy

 * Tariffs in the second Trump administration
   [/wiki/Tariffs_in_the_second_Trump_administration], Executive orders in the
   second presidency of Donald Trump
   [/wiki/List_of_executive_orders_in_the_second_presidency_of_Donald_Trump]
   * Executive Order 14257 [/wiki/Executive_Order_14257]
     * The second of two tariff [/wiki/Tariff] rounds go into effect in the
       United States [/wiki/United_States] containing country-specific tariffs
       [/wiki/Liberation_Day_tariffs] on goods into the country, including a
       104% tariff on Chinese [/wiki/China] imports. The first round of 10%
       blanket tariffs previously came into effect on April 5. (Reuters)
       [https://www.reuters.com/world/trumps-latest-tariffs-loom-set-deepen-global-trade-war-2025-04-09/]
     * China [/wiki/China]'s finance ministry
       [/wiki/Ministry_of_Finance_(China)] announces an increase from the
       previous 34% tariff to an 84% tariff on all goods imported from the U.S.
       (BBC News)
       [https://www.bbc.com/news/live/cp8vyy35g3mt?post=asset%3Aa5f6fd43-f285-4cef-8549-4b7ac5c517ef]
     * European Union [/wiki/European_Union] officials announce a set of
       retaliatory duties on U.S. imports from 10% to 25% on some U.S. goods.
       (NBC News)
       [https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/trump-administration/live-blog/trump-administration-live-updates-global-tariffs-china-rcna200346#rcrd76703]

Disasters and accidents

 * Jet Set nightclub roof collapse [/wiki/Jet_Set_nightclub_roof_collapse]
   * The number of deaths caused by the roof collapse
     [/wiki/Structural_integrity_and_failure] of the Jet Set nightclub in Santo
     Domingo [/wiki/Santo_Domingo], Dominican Republic
     [/wiki/Dominican_Republic], rises to 98. (La Nación)
     [https://www.lanacion.com.ar/agencias/sube-a-98-saldo-de-fallecidos-tras-colapso-de-discoteca-dominicana-nid09042025/]
     (Diario Libre)
     [https://www.diariolibre.com/actualidad/sucesos/2025/04/09/discoteca-jet-set-fallecidos-se-incrementan-a-98/3066030]

April 8, 2025 (2025-04-08) (Tuesday)
 * edit
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Current_events/2025_April_8&action=edit&editintro=Portal:Current_events/Edit_instructions]

Armed conflicts and attacks

 * Russo-Ukrainian War [/wiki/Russo-Ukrainian_War]
   * 2025 Belgorod Oblast incursion [/wiki/2025_Belgorod_Oblast_incursion]
     * Ukrainian [/wiki/Ukraine] president [/wiki/President_of_Ukraine]
       Volodymyr Zelenskyy [/wiki/Volodymyr_Zelenskyy] confirms the presence of
       Ukrainian troops [/wiki/Ukrainian_Armed_Forces] in Russia
       [/wiki/Russia]'s Belgorod Oblast [/wiki/Belgorod_Oblast]. (BBC News)
       [https://www.bbc.com/news/articles/cwy7dv6zk36o]

Disasters and accidents

 * Jet Set nightclub roof collapse [/wiki/Jet_Set_nightclub_roof_collapse]
   * At least 79 people, including former Major League Baseball
     [/wiki/Major_League_Baseball] players Tony Blanco [/wiki/Tony_Blanco] and
     Octavio Dotel [/wiki/Octavio_Dotel], are killed and 150 others are injured
     when the roof of a nightclub [/wiki/Nightclub] collapses during a
     performance by merengue singer [/wiki/Merengue_music] Rubby Pérez
     [/wiki/Rubby_P%C3%A9rez], who is among the dead, in Santo Domingo
     [/wiki/Santo_Domingo], Dominican Republic [/wiki/Dominican_Republic]. (NBC
     News)
     [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/13-dead-90-hospitalized-roof-dominican-republic-club-collapses-rcna200158]
     (El País)
     [https://elpais.com/america/2025-04-08/al-menos-15-muertos-y-mas-de-100-heridos-al-desplomarse-el-techo-de-una-discoteca-en-santo-domingo.html]
 * The death toll from the heavy flooding [/wiki/Flooding] in Kinshasa
   [/wiki/Kinshasa], Democratic Republic of the Congo
   [/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo], caused by overflow of the Ndjili
   River [/wiki/Ndjili_River] increases to 33 deaths. Hundreds of buildings are
   completely submerged and thousands of people are trapped in their homes.
   (NPR) [https://www.npr.org/2025/04/08/nx-s1-5355599/congo-kinshasa-flooding]
   (DW)
   [https://www.dw.com/en/heavy-flooding-in-kinshasa-kills-at-least-33-people/video-72170087]
 * About 50 hippos [/wiki/Hippo] are killed by anthrax [/wiki/Anthrax] poisoning
   at Virunga National Park [/wiki/Virunga_National_Park] in the Democratic
   Republic of the Congo [/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo]. (CTV News)
   [https://www.ctvnews.ca/climate-and-environment/article/anthrax-kills-50-hippos-in-africas-oldest-nature-reserve/]

Health and environment

 * 2020–2025 H5N1 outbreak [/wiki/2020%E2%80%932025_H5N1_outbreak]
   * Mexico [/wiki/Mexico] reports its first human death from bird flu
     [/wiki/Avian_influenza] subtype H5N1 [/wiki/Influenza_A_virus_subtype_H5N1]
     which caused multiple organ failure
     [/wiki/Multiple_organ_dysfunction_syndrome] in a three-year-old girl in
     Torreón [/wiki/Torre%C3%B3n], Coahuila [/wiki/Coahuila]. (Reuters)
     [https://www.reuters.com/world/americas/mexico-reports-first-human-death-h5n1-bird-flu-2025-04-08/]

Law and crime

 * 2024 Democratic Republic of the Congo coup attempt
   [/wiki/2024_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo_coup_attempt], Democratic
   Republic of the Congo–United States relations
   [/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo%E2%80%93United_States_relations]
   * Three U.S. citizens [/wiki/Citizenship_of_the_United_States] are commuted
     [/wiki/Commutation_(law)] of their crime of attempting a coup
     [/wiki/Coup_d%27%C3%A9tat] against the Congolese
     [/wiki/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo] President
     [/wiki/President_of_the_Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo] Félix Tshisekedi
     [/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Tshisekedi] in 2024 and extradited [/wiki/Extradition]
     back to the United States [/wiki/United_States]. They were previously
     sentenced to death [/wiki/Death_sentence] along with 34 others for the
     failed attempt that killed six people, including the coup's leader
     Christian Malanga [/wiki/Christian_Malanga]. (NPR)
     [https://www.npr.org/2025/04/08/nx-s1-5356069/american-drc-coup-plotters-us]
 * Mass shootings in the United States
   [/wiki/Mass_shootings_in_the_United_States]
   * Three people are killed and three others are injured in a mass shooting
     [/wiki/Mass_shooting] in Spotsylvania County
     [/wiki/Spotsylvania_County,_Virginia], Virginia [/wiki/Virginia], United
     States. (Fox News)
     [https://www.fox5dc.com/news/heavy-police-spotsylvania-county-neighborhood-shooting-possible]

Politics and elections

 * Asylum in Germany [/wiki/Asylum_in_Germany]
   * The German [/wiki/Germany] Federal Office for Migration and Refugees
     [/wiki/Federal_Office_for_Migration_and_Refugees] orders a temporary halt
     to a United Nations [/wiki/United_Nations_High_Commissioner_for_Refugees]
     refugee resettlement [/wiki/Third_country_resettlement] program which it
     has participated in since 2012, citing the change in government
     [/wiki/2025_German_federal_election]. The new coalition government
     [/wiki/German_governing_coalition] is expected to restart the program when
     a new interior minister [/wiki/Federal_Ministry_of_the_Interior_(Germany)]
     is announced. (DW)
     [https://www.dw.com/en/germany-orders-halt-on-un-refugee-resettlement-program/a-72171825]
 * Associated Press v. Budowich [/wiki/Associated_Press_v._Budowich], Second
   presidency of Donald Trump [/wiki/Second_presidency_of_Donald_Trump]
   * U.S. district judge [/wiki/United_States_federal_judge] for the District
     Court of D.C.
     [/wiki/United_States_District_Court_for_the_District_of_Columbia] Trevor N.
     McFadden [/wiki/Trevor_N._McFadden] orders the White House
     [/wiki/White_House] to restore the Associated Press
     [/wiki/Associated_Press]'s full access to cover presidential events on
     First Amendment [/wiki/First_Amendment] grounds, overruling the Trump
     administration [/wiki/Trump_administration]'s previous order to ban the
     news agency [/wiki/News_agency] after it refused to refer to the Gulf of
     Mexico [/wiki/Gulf_of_Mexico] as the "Gulf of America
     [/wiki/Executive_Order_14172]". (AP)
     [https://apnews.com/article/trump-ap-media-court-white-house-events-access-f346a0efe87c1dec4d6f90e6041abd09]
     (The Hill)
     [https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/5238923-trump-administration-ap-access/]

April 7, 2025 (2025-04-07) (Monday)
 * edit
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Portal:Current_events/2025_April_7&action=edit&editintro=Portal:Current_events/Edit_instructions]

Armed conflicts and attacks

 * Syrian civil war [/wiki/Syrian_civil_war]
   * Western Syria clashes
     [/wiki/Western_Syria_clashes_(December_2024%E2%80%93present)]
     * 2025 massacres of Syrian Alawites
       [/wiki/2025_massacres_of_Syrian_Alawites]
       * The number of mainly-Alawite [/wiki/Alawites] Syrian [/wiki/Syrians]
         civilians killed in ongoing sectarian
         [/wiki/Sectarianism_and_minorities_in_the_Syrian_civil_war] reprisal
         massacres [/wiki/Collective_punishment] by pro-Syrian government
         [/wiki/Second_Syrian_transitional_government] forces and Sunni
         [/wiki/Sunni_Islam] parties since March 6 rises to 1,767. (SOHR)
         [https://www.syriahr.com/%d8%b4%d9%87%d8%b1-%d9%83%d8%a7%d9%85%d9%84-%d8%b9%d9%84%d9%89-%d9%85%d8%b0%d8%a8%d8%ad%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d8%a7%d8%ad%d9%84-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%88%d8%b1%d9%8a-%d8%a8%d8%a7%d9%86%d8%aa%d8%b8/755870/]
 * Gaza war [/wiki/Gaza_war]
   * Israeli occupation of the Gaza Strip
     [/wiki/Israeli_occupation_of_the_Gaza_Strip]
     * Israel [/wiki/Israel] reportedly controls over half of the territory of
       the Gaza Strip [/wiki/Gaza_Strip] after razing [/wiki/Razing] multiple
       Palestinian properties to expand its buffer zone [/wiki/Buffer_zone].
       (AP)
       [https://apnews.com/article/gaza-buffer-zone-ceasefire-b7dada19483a3f8ef2fdecbc745ee6b5]
       (CNN)
       [https://www.cnn.com/2025/04/07/middleeast/israel-gaza-buffer-zone-troops-intl/index.html]
   * An Israeli [/wiki/Israel_Defense_Forces] airstrike [/wiki/Airstrike] near a
     charity kitchen in Gaza [/wiki/Gaza_Strip] where displaced
     [/wiki/Internal_displacement] Palestinians [/wiki/Palestinians] gather for
     food, kills more than 30 people. (AP)
     [https://apnews.com/article/israel-palestinians-hamas-war-news-ceasefire-hostages-04-07-2025-1ef0696b9c12bf18b5123ccd5b384a02]
 * Herder–farmer conflicts in Nigeria
   [/wiki/Herder%E2%80%93farmer_conflicts_in_Nigeria]
   * The National Emergency Management Agency
     [/wiki/National_Emergency_Management_Agency_(Nigeria)] reports that at
     least 52 people have been killed and over 2,000 others have been displaced
     from their homes in recent days in tit for tat [/wiki/Tit_for_tat] attacks
     by rival herders over control of arable land [/wiki/Arable_land] in Plateau
     State [/wiki/Plateau_State], Nigeria [/wiki/Nigeria]. (Reuters)
     [https://www.reuters.com/world/africa/gunmen-kill-least-52-people-nigerias-plateau-state-2025-04-07/]
 * Insurgency in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa [/wiki/Insurgency_in_Khyber_Pakhtunkhwa]
   * A Pakistan Army [/wiki/Pakistan_Army] raid on a Pakistani Taliban
     [/wiki/Pakistani_Taliban] militant hideout in Dera Ismail Khan
     [/wiki/Dera_Ismail_Khan], Khyber Pakhtunkhwa [/wiki/Khyber_Pakhtunkhwa],
     kills nine militants, including a high-profile Taliban leader who
     coordinated recent attacks on Pakistani military facilities in the region.
     (AP)
     [https://apnews.com/article/pakistan-security-raid-militants-killed-northwest-9c73a1b91b3697b4928870c7e4645671]

Help [/wiki/Help:Category]
From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Category.svg/120px-Category.svg.png]
This is a tracking category [/wiki/Category:Tracking_categories].
It is used to build and maintain a list or lists of pages—primarily for the sake
of the lists themselves and their use in article and category maintenance. It is
not part of the encyclopedia's categorization scheme
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization].
More information:
 * This category is hidden [/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization#Hiding_categories] on
   its member pages [/wiki/Category:Hidden_categories]—unless the corresponding
   user preference [/wiki/Special:Preferences#mw-prefsection-rendering]
   (Appearance → Show hidden categories) is set.
 * These categories are used to track, build and organize lists of pages needing
   "attention en masse" (for example, pages using deprecated syntax), or that
   may need to be edited at someone's earliest convenience.
 * These categories also serve to aggregate members of several lists or
   subcategories into a larger, more efficient list (discriminated by
   classifications).
 * Typically, tracking categories are automatically populated by templates
   invoked in pages or by the MediaWiki software (see Special:TrackingCategories
   [/wiki/Special:TrackingCategories] for an overview of the latter).

[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png]Administrators:
Please do not delete this category as empty!
This category may be empty occasionally or even most of the time.

The main page for this category [/wiki/Help:Categories] is WP:Short description
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Short_description].

This category contains articles with short descriptions that do not match the
description field on Wikidata.

No action is needed at this time. This is a tracking category only.

Joshua Schache (/ˈʃæki/ [/wiki/Help:IPA/English] SHAK-ee
[/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key];[1] born 21 August 1997) is an
Australian rules footballer [/wiki/Australian_rules_football] who formerly
played professionally for the Brisbane Lions [/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], the Western
Bulldogs [/wiki/Western_Bulldogs] and Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club]
in the Australian Football League [/wiki/Australian_Football_League] (AFL).


EARLY LIFE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]

Schache was born in Adelaide, South Australia [/wiki/Adelaide,_South_Australia]
to mother Rachel and father Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache].[2] He started
playing Auskick [/wiki/Auskick] when he was in grade five. He attended high
school at Assumption College Kilmore [/wiki/Assumption_College,_Kilmore] and
later Goulburn Valley Grammar School [/wiki/Goulburn_Valley_Grammar_School]. His
late father, Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache], also played with Brisbane in the
early 1990s.[3][4][5]

Josh spent his early youth as a ruckman/forward for the Seymour Lions, a club
based in the Seymour District Junior Football League. He played with the Murray
Bushrangers [/wiki/Murray_Bushrangers] in the TAC Cup [/wiki/TAC_Cup] until he
was selected to join the Brisbane Lions with the second pick in the 2015 AFL
draft [/wiki/2015_AFL_draft].[4]

Schache is left-footed, 199 centimetres (78 in) tall and weighs 96 kilograms
(212 lb).[6]

He won the Larke Medal [/wiki/Larke_Medal] for his performance in the NAB AFL
Under-18 Championships in 2015, where he also he kicked a record 24 goals.[6]


AFL CAREER

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=2]]

In the first two years of his career at the Brisbane Lions
[/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], Schache played 27 games and kicked 25 goals. During 2017
there was speculation that he would request a trade to a Victorian club, but at
the end of the season his manager shut down speculation, insisting that he would
not be requesting a trade. Despite this, Brisbane later announced they would be
exploring trade options for Schache in the forthcoming trade period. In the
final minutes of the trade period, Schache was traded to the Western Bulldogs
for pick 25 and 40 despite being contracted until 2019 at the Brisbane
Lions.[7]Schache overcame niggling injuries during the first half of 2018. After
strong performances in the VFL he was elevated to the senior side where he
finished the season with 17 goals in 13 games.[8]Schache had a breakout year in
2019, kicking 24 goals from 14 games, only being omitted from the side due to
concussion protocols. Schache played in the 2019 Elimination Final against club
rivals, Greater Western Sydney. After playing his career best year, Schache only
managed to play two senior games in 2020, kicking 2 goals.

After a one-off appearance earlier in 2021, he returned to the senior side in
the middle of the season, successfully moving to become a key defender.[9]
Schache managed to play every game for the rest of the year, as a defender too,
including the clubs impressive climb to the Grand Final. Schache was moved back
to the forward line for the 2021 finals [/wiki/2021_AFL_finals_series], kicking
4 goals and shutting down prominent key defenders such as Aliir Aliir
[/wiki/Aliir_Aliir] of Port Adelaide [/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club].[10] He
played in the Western Bulldogs' 2021 Grand Final [/wiki/2021_AFL_Grand_Final]
team.[11]

Following the 2022 AFL season [/wiki/2022_AFL_season], Schache was traded to
Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club] on the last day of the trade
period.[12] Schache managed only four games across two seasons for the Demons.
When Melbourne failed to make finals for the first time since 2020, Schache was
delisted at the conclusion of the 2024 AFL season [/wiki/2024_AFL_season].[13]

In 2025, Schache will play for the Doncaster East Football Club
[/wiki/Doncaster_East_Football_Club] in the Eastern Football Netball League
[/wiki/Eastern_Football_Netball_League] (EFNL).[14]

Joshua Schache (/ˈʃæki/ [/wiki/Help:IPA/English] SHAK-ee
[/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key];[1] born 21 August 1997) is an
Australian rules footballer [/wiki/Australian_rules_football] who formerly
played professionally for the Brisbane Lions [/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], the Western
Bulldogs [/wiki/Western_Bulldogs] and Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club]
in the Australian Football League [/wiki/Australian_Football_League] (AFL).


EARLY LIFE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]

Schache was born in Adelaide, South Australia [/wiki/Adelaide,_South_Australia]
to mother Rachel and father Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache].[2] He started
playing Auskick [/wiki/Auskick] when he was in grade five. He attended high
school at Assumption College Kilmore [/wiki/Assumption_College,_Kilmore] and
later Goulburn Valley Grammar School [/wiki/Goulburn_Valley_Grammar_School]. His
late father, Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache], also played with Brisbane in the
early 1990s.[3][4][5]

Josh spent his early youth as a ruckman/forward for the Seymour Lions, a club
based in the Seymour District Junior Football League. He played with the Murray
Bushrangers [/wiki/Murray_Bushrangers] in the TAC Cup [/wiki/TAC_Cup] until he
was selected to join the Brisbane Lions with the second pick in the 2015 AFL
draft [/wiki/2015_AFL_draft].[4]

Schache is left-footed, 199 centimetres (78 in) tall and weighs 96 kilograms
(212 lb).[6]

He won the Larke Medal [/wiki/Larke_Medal] for his performance in the NAB AFL
Under-18 Championships in 2015, where he also he kicked a record 24 goals.[6]


AFL CAREER

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=2]]

In the first two years of his career at the Brisbane Lions
[/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], Schache played 27 games and kicked 25 goals. During 2017
there was speculation that he would request a trade to a Victorian club, but at
the end of the season his manager shut down speculation, insisting that he would
not be requesting a trade. Despite this, Brisbane later announced they would be
exploring trade options for Schache in the forthcoming trade period. In the
final minutes of the trade period, Schache was traded to the Western Bulldogs
for pick 25 and 40 despite being contracted until 2019 at the Brisbane
Lions.[7]Schache overcame niggling injuries during the first half of 2018. After
strong performances in the VFL he was elevated to the senior side where he
finished the season with 17 goals in 13 games.[8]Schache had a breakout year in
2019, kicking 24 goals from 14 games, only being omitted from the side due to
concussion protocols. Schache played in the 2019 Elimination Final against club
rivals, Greater Western Sydney. After playing his career best year, Schache only
managed to play two senior games in 2020, kicking 2 goals.

After a one-off appearance earlier in 2021, he returned to the senior side in
the middle of the season, successfully moving to become a key defender.[9]
Schache managed to play every game for the rest of the year, as a defender too,
including the clubs impressive climb to the Grand Final. Schache was moved back
to the forward line for the 2021 finals [/wiki/2021_AFL_finals_series], kicking
4 goals and shutting down prominent key defenders such as Aliir Aliir
[/wiki/Aliir_Aliir] of Port Adelaide [/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club].[10] He
played in the Western Bulldogs' 2021 Grand Final [/wiki/2021_AFL_Grand_Final]
team.[11]

Following the 2022 AFL season [/wiki/2022_AFL_season], Schache was traded to
Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club] on the last day of the trade
period.[12] Schache managed only four games across two seasons for the Demons.
When Melbourne failed to make finals for the first time since 2020, Schache was
delisted at the conclusion of the 2024 AFL season [/wiki/2024_AFL_season].[13]

In 2025, Schache will play for the Doncaster East Football Club
[/wiki/Doncaster_East_Football_Club] in the Eastern Football Netball League
[/wiki/Eastern_Football_Netball_League] (EFNL).[14]

Appearance
move to sidebar hide
Help [/wiki/Help:Category]
From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/Category.svg/120px-Category.svg.png]
This is a tracking category [/wiki/Category:Tracking_categories].
It is used to build and maintain a list or lists of pages—primarily for the sake
of the lists themselves and their use in article and category maintenance. It is
not part of the encyclopedia's categorization scheme
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization].
More information:
 * This category is hidden [/wiki/Wikipedia:Categorization#Hiding_categories] on
   its member pages [/wiki/Category:Hidden_categories]—unless the corresponding
   user preference [/wiki/Special:Preferences#mw-prefsection-rendering]
   (Appearance → Show hidden categories) is set.
 * These categories are used to track, build and organize lists of pages needing
   "attention en masse" (for example, pages using deprecated syntax), or that
   may need to be edited at someone's earliest convenience.
 * These categories also serve to aggregate members of several lists or
   subcategories into a larger, more efficient list (discriminated by
   classifications).
 * Typically, tracking categories are automatically populated by templates
   invoked in pages or by the MediaWiki software (see Special:TrackingCategories
   [/wiki/Special:TrackingCategories] for an overview of the latter).

[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png]Administrators:
Please do not delete this category as empty!
This category may be empty occasionally or even most of the time.

The main page for this category [/wiki/Help:Categories] is WP:Short description
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Short_description].

This category contains articles with short descriptions that do not match the
description field on Wikidata.

No action is needed at this time. This is a tracking category only.

Joshua Schache (/ˈʃæki/ [/wiki/Help:IPA/English] SHAK-ee
[/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key];[1] born 21 August 1997) is an
Australian rules footballer [/wiki/Australian_rules_football] who formerly
played professionally for the Brisbane Lions [/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], the Western
Bulldogs [/wiki/Western_Bulldogs] and Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club]
in the Australian Football League [/wiki/Australian_Football_League] (AFL).


EARLY LIFE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]

Schache was born in Adelaide, South Australia [/wiki/Adelaide,_South_Australia]
to mother Rachel and father Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache].[2] He started
playing Auskick [/wiki/Auskick] when he was in grade five. He attended high
school at Assumption College Kilmore [/wiki/Assumption_College,_Kilmore] and
later Goulburn Valley Grammar School [/wiki/Goulburn_Valley_Grammar_School]. His
late father, Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache], also played with Brisbane in the
early 1990s.[3][4][5]

Josh spent his early youth as a ruckman/forward for the Seymour Lions, a club
based in the Seymour District Junior Football League. He played with the Murray
Bushrangers [/wiki/Murray_Bushrangers] in the TAC Cup [/wiki/TAC_Cup] until he
was selected to join the Brisbane Lions with the second pick in the 2015 AFL
draft [/wiki/2015_AFL_draft].[4]

Schache is left-footed, 199 centimetres (78 in) tall and weighs 96 kilograms
(212 lb).[6]

He won the Larke Medal [/wiki/Larke_Medal] for his performance in the NAB AFL
Under-18 Championships in 2015, where he also he kicked a record 24 goals.[6]


AFL CAREER

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=2]]

In the first two years of his career at the Brisbane Lions
[/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], Schache played 27 games and kicked 25 goals. During 2017
there was speculation that he would request a trade to a Victorian club, but at
the end of the season his manager shut down speculation, insisting that he would
not be requesting a trade. Despite this, Brisbane later announced they would be
exploring trade options for Schache in the forthcoming trade period. In the
final minutes of the trade period, Schache was traded to the Western Bulldogs
for pick 25 and 40 despite being contracted until 2019 at the Brisbane
Lions.[7]Schache overcame niggling injuries during the first half of 2018. After
strong performances in the VFL he was elevated to the senior side where he
finished the season with 17 goals in 13 games.[8]Schache had a breakout year in
2019, kicking 24 goals from 14 games, only being omitted from the side due to
concussion protocols. Schache played in the 2019 Elimination Final against club
rivals, Greater Western Sydney. After playing his career best year, Schache only
managed to play two senior games in 2020, kicking 2 goals.

After a one-off appearance earlier in 2021, he returned to the senior side in
the middle of the season, successfully moving to become a key defender.[9]
Schache managed to play every game for the rest of the year, as a defender too,
including the clubs impressive climb to the Grand Final. Schache was moved back
to the forward line for the 2021 finals [/wiki/2021_AFL_finals_series], kicking
4 goals and shutting down prominent key defenders such as Aliir Aliir
[/wiki/Aliir_Aliir] of Port Adelaide [/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club].[10] He
played in the Western Bulldogs' 2021 Grand Final [/wiki/2021_AFL_Grand_Final]
team.[11]

Following the 2022 AFL season [/wiki/2022_AFL_season], Schache was traded to
Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club] on the last day of the trade
period.[12] Schache managed only four games across two seasons for the Demons.
When Melbourne failed to make finals for the first time since 2020, Schache was
delisted at the conclusion of the 2024 AFL season [/wiki/2024_AFL_season].[13]

In 2025, Schache will play for the Doncaster East Football Club
[/wiki/Doncaster_East_Football_Club] in the Eastern Football Netball League
[/wiki/Eastern_Football_Netball_League] (EFNL).[14]

Josh Schache
Add languages >

The popularity (frequency) distribution of given names typically follows a power
law distribution [/wiki/Zipf%E2%80%93Mandelbrot_law].

Since about 1800 in England and Wales and in the U.S., the popularity
distribution of given names has been shifting so that the most popular names are
losing popularity. For example, in England and Wales, the most popular female
and male names given to babies born in 1800 were Mary and John, with 24% of
female babies and 22% of male babies receiving those names, respectively.[32] In
contrast, the corresponding statistics for England and Wales in 1994 were Emily
and James, with 3% and 4% of names, respectively. Not only have Mary and John
gone out of favour in the English-speaking world, but the overall distribution
of names has also changed significantly over the last 100 years for females, but
not for males. This has led to an increasing amount of diversity for female
names.[33]


CHOICE OF NAMES

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=9]]

Education, ethnicity, religion, class and political ideology affect parents'
choice of names. Politically conservative parents choose common and traditional
names, while politically liberal parents may choose the names of literary
characters or other relatively obscure cultural figures.[34] Devout members of
religions often choose names from their religious scriptures. For example, Hindu
parents may name a daughter Saanvi [/wiki/Saanvi] after the goddess, Jewish
parents may name a boy Isaac [/wiki/Isaac] after one of the earliest ancestral
figures, and Muslim parents may name a boy Mohammed [/wiki/Mohammed_(name)]
after the prophet Mohammed [/wiki/Muhammad].

There are many tools parents can use to choose names, including books, websites
and applications. An example is the Baby Name Game that uses the Elo rating
system [/wiki/Elo_rating_system] to rank parents preferred names and help them
select one.[35]


INFLUENCE OF POPULAR CULTURE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=10]]
[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/60px-Question_book-new.svg.png]/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg
This section needs additional citations for verification
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability]. Please help improve this article
[/wiki/Special:EditPage/Given_name] by adding citations to reliable sources
[/wiki/Help:Referencing_for_beginners] in this section. Unsourced material may
be challenged and removed. (October 2015) (Learn how and when to remove this
message [/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal])

Popular culture [/wiki/Popular_culture] appears to have an influence on naming
trends, at least in the United States and United Kingdom. Newly famous
celebrities and public figures may influence the popularity of names. For
example, in 2004, the names "Keira" and "Kiera" (anglicisation of Irish name
Ciara) respectively became the 51st and 92nd most popular girls' names in the
UK, following the rise in popularity of British actress Keira Knightley
[/wiki/Keira_Knightley].[36] In 2001, the use of Colby as a boys' name for
babies in the United States jumped from 233rd place to 99th, just after Colby
Donaldson [/wiki/Colby_Donaldson] was the runner-up on Survivor: The Australian
Outback [/wiki/Survivor:_The_Australian_Outback].[citation needed
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]] Also, the female name "Miley" which before
was not in the top 1000 was 278th most popular in 2007, following the rise to
fame of singer-actress Miley Cyrus [/wiki/Miley_Cyrus] (who was named Destiny at
birth).[37]

[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b0/Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svg/500px-Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svg.png]/wiki/File:Influence_of_TV_series_on_given_names.svgInfluence
of TV series on given names in England and Wales from 1996 to 2021.

Characters from fiction also seem to influence naming. After the name Kayla
[/wiki/Kayla_(name)] was used for a character [/wiki/Kayla_Brady] on the
American soap opera [/wiki/Soap_opera] Days of Our Lives
[/wiki/Days_of_Our_Lives], the name's popularity increased greatly. The name
Tammy [/wiki/Tammy_(given_name)], and the related Tamara
[/wiki/Tamara_(given_name)] became popular after the movie Tammy and the
Bachelor [/wiki/Tammy_and_the_Bachelor] came out in 1957. Some names were
established or spread by being used in literature. Notable examples include
Pamela [/wiki/Pamela_(name)], invented by Sir Philip Sidney
[/wiki/Philip_Sidney] for a pivotal character in his epic prose work, The
Countess of Pembroke's Arcadia [/wiki/The_Countess_of_Pembroke%27s_Arcadia];
Jessica [/wiki/Jessica_(given_name)], created by William Shakespeare in his play
The Merchant of Venice [/wiki/The_Merchant_of_Venice]; Vanessa
[/wiki/Vanessa_(name)], created by Jonathan Swift [/wiki/Jonathan_Swift]; Fiona
[/wiki/Fiona], a character from James Macpherson [/wiki/James_Macpherson]'s
spurious cycle of Ossian [/wiki/Ossian] poems; Wendy [/wiki/Wendy], an obscure
name popularised by J. M. Barrie [/wiki/J._M._Barrie] in his play Peter Pan, or
The Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up
[/wiki/Peter_Pan,_or_The_Boy_Who_Wouldn%27t_Grow_Up]; and Madison
[/wiki/Madison_(name)], a character from the movie Splash [/wiki/Splash_(film)].
Lara [/wiki/Lara_(name)] and Larissa [/wiki/Larissa_(given_name)] were rare in
America before the appearance of Doctor Zhivago
[/wiki/Doctor_Zhivago_(1965_film)], and have become fairly common since.

Songs can influence the naming of children. Jude jumped from 814th most popular
male name in 1968 to 668th in 1969, following the release of the Beatles
[/wiki/The_Beatles]' "Hey Jude [/wiki/Hey_Jude]". Similarly, Layla [/wiki/Layla]
charted as 969th most popular in 1972 after the Eric Clapton
[/wiki/Eric_Clapton] song. It had not been in the top 1,000 before.[37] Kayleigh
became a particularly popular name in the United Kingdom following the release
of a song by the British rock group Marillion [/wiki/Marillion]. Government
statistics in 2005 revealed that 96% of Kayleighs were born after 1985, the year
in which Marillion released "Kayleigh [/wiki/Kayleigh]". [citation needed
[/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed]]

Popular culture figures need not be admirable in order to influence naming
trends. For example, Peyton came into the top 1000 as a female given name for
babies in the United States for the first time in 1992 (at #583), immediately
after it was featured as the name of an evil nanny in the film The Hand That
Rocks the Cradle [/wiki/The_Hand_That_Rocks_the_Cradle_(1992_film)].[37] On the
other hand, historical events can influence child-naming. For example, the given
name Adolf [/wiki/Adolf] has fallen out of use since the end of World War II
[/wiki/World_War_II] in 1945.

In contrast with this anecdotal evidence, a comprehensive study of Norwegian
first name datasets[38] shows that the main factors that govern first name
dynamics are endogenous [/wiki/Endogenous]. Monitoring the popularity of 1,000
names over 130 years, the authors have identified only five cases of exogenous
[/wiki/Exogenous] effects, three of them are connected to the names given to the
babies of the Norwegian royal family.


20TH CENTURY AFRICAN-AMERICAN NAMES

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=11]]

Since the civil rights movement of 1950–1970, African-American names
[/wiki/African-American_names] given to children have strongly mirrored
sociopolitical movements and philosophies in the African-American community.
Since the 1970s neologistic (creative, inventive) practices have become
increasingly common and the subject of academic study.[39]

NOTES

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=13]]
 1. ^ However, the family name – given name order is used only in informal or
    traditional contexts. The official naming order in Austria [/wiki/Austria]
    and Bavaria [/wiki/Bavaria] is given name – family name.
 2. ^ Protesting Swedish naming laws, in 1996, two parents attempted to name
    their child Brfxxccxxmnpcccclllmmnprxvclmnckssqlbb11116
    [/wiki/Naming_law_in_Sweden#Protest_names], stating that it was "a pregnant,
    expressionistic development that we see as an artistic creation".[6]


REFERENCES

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Given_name&action=edit&section=14]]
 1.  ^ a b c Grigg, John [/wiki/John_Grigg] (2 November 1991). "The Times"
     [/wiki/The_Times]. In the last century and well into the present one,
     grown-up British people, with rare exceptions, addressed each other by
     their surnames. What we now call first names (then Christian names) were
     very little used outside the family. Men who became friends would drop the
     Mr and use their bare surnames as a mark of intimacy: e.g. Holmes
     [/wiki/Sherlock_Holmes] and Watson [/wiki/Dr._Watson]. First names were
     only generally used for, and among, children. Today we have gone to the
     other extreme. People tend to be on first-name terms from the moment of
     introduction, and surnames are often hardly mentioned. Moreover, first
     names are relentlessly abbreviated, particularly in the media: Susan
     becomes Sue [/wiki/Sue_Lawley], Terrence Terry [/wiki/Terry_Wogan] and
     Robert Bob [/wiki/Bob_Holness] not only to friends and relations, but to
     millions who know these people only as faces and/or voices. quoted in
     Burchfield, R. W. [/wiki/Robert_Burchfield] (1996). The New Fowler's Modern
     English Usage [https://archive.org/details/newfowlersmodern00fowl]
     (3rd ed.). Oxford University Press. p. 512. ISBN
     [/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)] 978-0199690367

 38. ^ Kessler, David A.; Maruvka, Yosi E.; Ouren, Jøergen; Shnerb, Nadav M. (20
     June 2012). "You Name It – How Memory and Delay Govern First Name Dynamics"
     [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3380031]. PLOS ONE. 7 (6):
     e38790. Bibcode [/wiki/Bibcode_(identifier)]:2012PLoSO...738790K
     [https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2012PLoSO...738790K]. doi
     [/wiki/Doi_(identifier)]:10.1371/journal.pone.0038790
     [https://doi.org/10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0038790]. PMC
     [/wiki/PMC_(identifier)] 3380031
     [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3380031]. PMID
     [/wiki/PMID_(identifier)] 22745679
     [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22745679].
 39. ^ Gaddis, S. (2017). "How Black Are Lakisha and Jamal? Racial Perceptions
     from Names Used in Correspondence Audit Studies"
     [https://osf.io/7c4wv/download]. Sociological Science. 4: 469–489. doi
     [/wiki/Doi_(identifier)]:10.15195/v4.a19
     [https://doi.org/10.15195%2Fv4.a19].

Joshua Schache (/ˈʃæki/ [/wiki/Help:IPA/English] SHAK-ee
[/wiki/Help:Pronunciation_respelling_key];[1] born 21 August 1997) is an
Australian rules footballer [/wiki/Australian_rules_football] who formerly
played professionally for the Brisbane Lions [/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], the Western
Bulldogs [/wiki/Western_Bulldogs] and Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club]
in the Australian Football League [/wiki/Australian_Football_League] (AFL).


EARLY LIFE

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=1]]

Schache was born in Adelaide, South Australia [/wiki/Adelaide,_South_Australia]
to mother Rachel and father Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache].[2] He started
playing Auskick [/wiki/Auskick] when he was in grade five. He attended high
school at Assumption College Kilmore [/wiki/Assumption_College,_Kilmore] and
later Goulburn Valley Grammar School [/wiki/Goulburn_Valley_Grammar_School]. His
late father, Laurence [/wiki/Laurence_Schache], also played with Brisbane in the
early 1990s.[3][4][5]

Josh spent his early youth as a ruckman/forward for the Seymour Lions, a club
based in the Seymour District Junior Football League. He played with the Murray
Bushrangers [/wiki/Murray_Bushrangers] in the TAC Cup [/wiki/TAC_Cup] until he
was selected to join the Brisbane Lions with the second pick in the 2015 AFL
draft [/wiki/2015_AFL_draft].[4]

Schache is left-footed, 199 centimetres (78 in) tall and weighs 96 kilograms
(212 lb).[6]

He won the Larke Medal [/wiki/Larke_Medal] for his performance in the NAB AFL
Under-18 Championships in 2015, where he also he kicked a record 24 goals.[6]


AFL CAREER

[edit [/w/index.php?title=Josh_Schache&action=edit&section=2]]

In the first two years of his career at the Brisbane Lions
[/wiki/Brisbane_Lions], Schache played 27 games and kicked 25 goals. During 2017
there was speculation that he would request a trade to a Victorian club, but at
the end of the season his manager shut down speculation, insisting that he would
not be requesting a trade. Despite this, Brisbane later announced they would be
exploring trade options for Schache in the forthcoming trade period. In the
final minutes of the trade period, Schache was traded to the Western Bulldogs
for pick 25 and 40 despite being contracted until 2019 at the Brisbane
Lions.[7]Schache overcame niggling injuries during the first half of 2018. After
strong performances in the VFL he was elevated to the senior side where he
finished the season with 17 goals in 13 games.[8]Schache had a breakout year in
2019, kicking 24 goals from 14 games, only being omitted from the side due to
concussion protocols. Schache played in the 2019 Elimination Final against club
rivals, Greater Western Sydney. After playing his career best year, Schache only
managed to play two senior games in 2020, kicking 2 goals.

After a one-off appearance earlier in 2021, he returned to the senior side in
the middle of the season, successfully moving to become a key defender.[9]
Schache managed to play every game for the rest of the year, as a defender too,
including the clubs impressive climb to the Grand Final. Schache was moved back
to the forward line for the 2021 finals [/wiki/2021_AFL_finals_series], kicking
4 goals and shutting down prominent key defenders such as Aliir Aliir
[/wiki/Aliir_Aliir] of Port Adelaide [/wiki/Port_Adelaide_Football_Club].[10] He
played in the Western Bulldogs' 2021 Grand Final [/wiki/2021_AFL_Grand_Final]
team.[11]

Following the 2022 AFL season [/wiki/2022_AFL_season], Schache was traded to
Melbourne [/wiki/Melbourne_Football_Club] on the last day of the trade
period.[12] Schache managed only four games across two seasons for the Demons.
When Melbourne failed to make finals for the first time since 2020, Schache was
delisted at the conclusion of the 2024 AFL season [/wiki/2024_AFL_season].[13]

In 2025, Schache will play for the Doncaster East Football Club
[/wiki/Doncaster_East_Football_Club] in the Eastern Football Netball League
[/wiki/Eastern_Football_Netball_League] (EFNL).[14]
